Replication of Economic Insecurity Increases Physical Pain by Chou et al. (2016, Psychological Science)

Author

Jordan Troutman (troutman@cs.stanford.edu)

Published

December 12, 2023

Introduction

This project replicates part of a behavioral psychology study which inquires about if socioeconomic status has physical effects on the body. The initial publication from Chou et al. (2016) conducted a total of six studies, and a meta-analysis on various causal pathways to explain the phenomena. This project focuses on replicating the fifth study, which asks if the degree of control one feels they have affects how much physical pain they feel. Participants are placed into conditions where they have to recall experiences when they had either a high or low sense of control. They then report the amount of physical pain they feel after the recollection period. Differences between the two conditions are then compared.

Materials and Data

Materials, data, and experimental protocols can be reached at the following links:

  • Pre-Registration: https://osf.io/vmfue
  • Survey: https://stanforduniversity.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_b0ZGaA73CKWMnzw
  • Code and Data: https://github.com/psych251/chou2016_rescue

First Replication Attempt

This project is a replication inspired by a replication conducted by Zion, 2017. In this replication, the author follows the protocol closely to the initial study described in the article; the survey material is mostly similar, and participants are recruited from the same platform (Amazon Mechanical Turk).
The author deviates by adding manipulation checks to determine if participants have a clear understanding of what it means to have a high or low sense of control. This is mainly done by asking participants five questions relating to sense of control that are included in the other studies from the initial publication. After a successful manipulation check, the author was unable to replicate the results of the initial publication; there was no significant difference between the average pain levels in each group. Zion performs further analysis by collecting from participants painkiller use and if this is a potential control for pain levels that participants report.

Summary of prior replication attempt

Based on the prior write-up, describe any differences between the original and 1st replication in terms of methods, sample, sample size, and analysis. Note any potential problems such as exclusion rates, noisy data, or issues with analysis.

The first replication aimed to keep their iteration as close to the initial study as possible, given the information in the article. At a high level, the replication project recieves samples through Amazon Mechanical Turk (MTurk), then assigns them to either the high or low control conditions. They then measure average reported pain levels within each group, and conducted a t test and determined effect size using cohenâs d.

The replication study mainly deviates from the initial study within their procedures and, subsequently, their analysis. At the end of their study, the replication asks five additional questions which âcaptures respondentsâ psychological sense of lacking control.â The average of those questionsis used as an additional control within the analysis. Additionally, the replication asks participants if they have used painkillers and the type/frequency of them.

Within the analysis, the replication observes the group averages of the psychological sense of lacking control to ensure the treatment condition actually intervenes on a sense of control, rather than intervening on the specific instances participants are thinking of, which generally could be more painful independent of the amount of control they have.

Another factor to note is the replication increases the sample size, since the initial study was under-powered (post-hoc).

Both the replication and the initial study do not seem to take into consideration the painkiller use within the random treatment of groups. If it is believed that painkillers can alter a participantâs repsonse to the questions of pain, it would be important to know how many people per group are taking painkillers. This would introduce painkillers as something that could affect (mediate) the captured measure based upon group association.

Methods

Materials

The materials used in this study closely align with both the initial studyâs description and replication. The following excerpts describe the materials:

âParticipants were asked to write about an autobiographical experience (Whitson & Galinsky, 2008). Half recalled a time when they lacked control. The other half recalled a time when they had complete control.

After the recall task, participants were asked to âchoose the overall pain level that best describes how much physical pain you are experiencing RIGHT NOW.â They responded using a visual slider scale (Portenoy & Kanner, 1996), on which 0 indicated no pain and 100 indicated the worst pain ever experienced.

Participants also reported their age, gender, and current employment status, and whether they were using painkillers.â

âSubjects then completed a short, five-item measure of control, that was an additional scale added to the authorâs original procedure. See Differences from Original Study section for more details.â (Zion)

Exact survey materials can be accessed at the provided links above.

Procedure

The procedure in this replication attempt closely aligns with the initial study and replication. Participants are first asked to a set of pre-survey questions regarding how much pain they would feel experiencing a set of stimuli (e.g. getting hit by a pillow, stepping on a nail, getting hand burned, etc.) They are then are randomly assigned to Group A or Group B. In Group A (high-control), participants are asked to recount a time when they were in complete control of a situation. In Group B (low-control), participants are asked to do the opposite â namely recount a time they felt âa complete lack of control.â Both groups then spend a few minutes reflecting on these incidents, and then are asked to indicate the level of physical pain (on a scale of 0 - 100) they are experiencing. Participants are then asked to report how often they take painkillers during a month, the types of painkillers, along with demographic factors (sex, age, employment type, and race).

Controls

Within the pre-survey questions, one attention check is included which states âPlease answer 50. On a scale of 0 - 100, where would you put getting hit by a ball?â Overall, the pre-survey section is a calibration and a method of understanding how a participants internalize the pain scale.
Asking each participant to then state their current level of pain pre-intervention provides a stronger baseline to the effect of the intervention.

Analysis Plan

Summary statistics for overall and per-condition are reported, as in the original study. The original study and replication study make no note of any data cleaning or exclusion rules. If participants do not pass the attention check, their input will not be included.

Average pain levels (post-intervention) will be reported, as well as regression models adding controls for age, gender, employment status, and painkiller use. The key analysis of interest is the two-sampled t-test between conditions (high sense of control vs low sense of control). Cohenâs d score is also reported.

Planned Sample

The plan is to use Prolific to recruit participants. To control for participation quality, Prolific participants are picked with high (>95%) approval ratings.

Power Analysis

The results from the initial paper compares the average pain levels between the conditions (control vs. lack of control). A two-tailed two-sample t-test is used to determine if the sample means between the two groups are statistically different from each other.

The intial paper reports a t=2.94 Cohenâs d effect size of 0.41. Additionally, the first replication reports a t=0.55 effect size of d=0.191 with 156 samples in total (78 per group).
Post-hoc, the initial study was indeed under powered with a power of 0.53. The replication has a power of 0.93.

Running a power analysis on the initial report, the following sample sizes would have been required to gain the calculated effect size (for groups of equal sizes):

  • Power = 80%: n = 95 per group
  • Power = 90%: n = 126 per group
  • Power = 95%: n = 156 per group

Though the replication did have a well-powered experiment, the sample size is lower than the size needed for 80% power; it is a bit conservative with respect to conducting a replication. As a result, this study aims to have n=125 participants per group, which is 2.5x the original sample size. According to the power-analysis, a-priori, this is well-powered and has a substantially larger sample than the initial, which is a safe method to test the reproducibility of an experiment.

Differences from Original Study and First Replication

This replication mainly varies from the original study and first replication by asking participants pre-survey questions about pain levels. A challenge of this study seem mostly related to assessing the level of severity of their specific memory; some individuals in Group B may recall very painful memories, while some may not. It is also a challenge to determine if the pain they experience is directly attributed to the intervention, or if circumstances like environment and initial pain levels before impact the final measurement. Capturing their understanding of pain before the intervention can help to stabilize responses, and also be used for data exploration. Additionally, the first two studies recruit participants on Mechanical Turk, while this study recruits participants from Prolific. Participants within Prolific have to be within the U.S., be fluent in English, and have an approval rating of at least 95% to be in the study (matching the criteria for the original and first replication).

Methods Addendum (Post Data Collection)

Actual Sample

A total of 266 participants were recruited for the study. In total, 252 participants passed attention checks, and were used in the analysis. More participants were recruited in order to get the desired amount of participants per group from the power analysis.

Results

Survey data is read, parsed, and prepared for analysis. Participants who do not pass the attention check are removed here. Experiment condition is also indicated here.

Key Analysis: Pain Levels Amongst Sense of Control

The average pain levels are reported after being prompted to think about a time of either high or low control. 131 participants were asked to think about a time when they had a high sense of control, while 121 participants were asked to think about a time when they had a low sense of control.

  df |> group_by(condition) |> summarize(avg = mean(`Pain Level_1`), size = n())
# A tibble: 2 Ã 3
  condition   avg  size
  <chr>     <dbl> <int>
1 High       10.4   131
2 Low        11.5   121
  boxplot(`Pain Level_1` ~ condition, data = df)

The low control condition has an average pain rating of 11.52. The high control condition has an average pain rating of 10.40. The t-test fails to reject the null hypothesis; there is not sufficient evidence to support that the average ratings between the two groups are different. The effect size is reported to be -0.064 with a 95% confidence interval of (-0.31, 0.18).

control <- df |> filter(condition == "Low") |> select(`Pain Level_1`)
intervention <- df |> filter(condition == "High") |> select(`Pain Level_1`)

Calibration Check

This check aims to determine if participants have a general understanding of how to rate pain levels. The following plot shows the distribution of pain levels conditioned by stimuli.

  # Plot manipulation check by grouping pain levels based on stimuli
  compare_df <- df |> 
      rename(Pillow=`1_Q14_1`, Nail=`2_Q14_1` , Bee=`3_Q14_1`, Scratch=`4_Q14_1`, Burn=`5_Q14_1`) |>
      pivot_longer(c(Pillow, Nail, Bee, Scratch, Burn), names_to = "Group", values_to = "Pain") |>
      select(Group, Pain, condition)

  ggplot(compare_df, aes(x=Group, y=Pain)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    geom_point(alpha=0.1) +
    ggtitle("Baseline Pain Levels") +
    xlab("Stimulus") +
    theme_classic()

It can be observed that stimuli that are more painful (e.g. getting stung by a bee burning a hand, stepping on a nail) have higher levels of pain reported compared to less painful stimuli (getting hit by a pillow or getting scratched). A pairwise t-test shows each stimuli is statistically significant from one another (excluding pillow x scratch). This calibration check indicates that given conditions to think about, participants are able to discern the amount of pain they would feel on the given scale.

# Compare pairwise if the difference in pairwise means are significant
pairwise.t.test(compare_df$Pain, compare_df$Group, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

Confirmatory analysis

The three tests are compared against each other. The averages per condition show that the original study does find a significant difference. The first replication and this replication (rescue) fail to find significant results. This iteration does have comparable sample statistics to the initial publication, though they are not sigificant.

results <- df |> group_by(condition) |> summarize(
  Mean=mean(`Pain Level_1`, na.rm = TRUE),
  Sd = sd(`Pain Level_1`, na.rm = TRUE),
  N = n()
)

control_results <- results[which(results$condition == "Low"),]
intervention_results <- results[which(results$condition == "High"),]

comparison_df<-data.frame(
  Mean=c(13.75,6.57,23.1,18.51, control_results$Mean, intervention_results$Mean), 
  sd=c(21.49,11.62,23.88,23.88,control_results$Sd, intervention_results$Sd), 
  Study=as.factor(c("Original","Original","Replication","Replication","Rescue", "Rescue")),
  Condition=c("Low Control","High Control","Low Control","High Control","Low Control", "High Control"),
  Insert= c(0.0, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0),
  N=c(50,50,72,86,control_results$N, intervention_results$N)
  ) 
  
  
ggplot(comparison_df, aes(x=Study, y=Mean, fill=Condition)) +

Discussion

Mini meta analysis

A meta analysis can be conducted across the three studies. There seem to be no other replications of this paper in publication. Combining across the original paper, 1st replication, and 2nd replication, what is the aggregate effect size?

cohen_d_replication <- psych::d.ci(0.1906083, n1=78, n2=78)
cohen_d_initial <- psych::d.ci(0.41, n1=50, n2=50)
cohen_d_initial[,c("effect")]
effect 
  0.41 
meta_df <- data.frame(
  name=c("Original", "Replication", "Rescue"),
  d=c(cohen_d_initial[,c("effect")], cohen_d_replication[,c("effect")], cohen_d_rescue$estimate),
  n=c(100, 156, nrow(df)),
  upper=c(cohen_d_initial[,c("upper")], cohen_d_replication[,c("upper")], cohen_d_rescue$conf.int[c("upper")]),
  lower=c(cohen_d_initial[,c("lower")], cohen_d_replication[,c("lower")], cohen_d_rescue$conf.int[c("lower")])
)

meta_df <- meta_df |> mutate(sd=sqrt(n) * (upper-lower) / 3.92) |> mutate(var=sd^2)
re_model <- rma(yi = d, vi = var, data = meta_df, method = "REML", knha = TRUE)

The three studies generate an overall effect size that is slightly positive, but with a lower confidence bound being negative; there is not enough confidence to demonstrate that the effect is larger than zero. ### Summary of Replication Attempt

The primary finding from this replication attempt is that there is not evidence to support the rejection of the difference in group means. Simply put, this replication was unable to produce results similar to the initial study. A possible reason why this study did not replicate is due to the pre-survey questions. It can be argued that the pre-survey is priming the participant before the intervention. But when looking at how participants responded (pre- vs post-intervention), the two groups had consistent outcomes; many people did not shift pain levels (relative to the baseline of pillow taps). Though the replication study and this study generate the same outcome, it is possible that the initial study performed a survey that was different from the simple description described in the paper.

Commentary

The exploratory analysis showed that participants responded pretty similarly among groups. This could be a confound of the pre-survey, but is likely not because the pre-survey is in a sense more of a practice. The study did not replicate from the original, but it did produce the same results as the first replication. This could be an indication that the first study was lucky, or there were many iterations of the study and the final version with really promising results is shown. There are definitely differences between the studies, and is likely within the survey design; because all studies use comparable platforms, and the two replication studies almost perfectly mirror each other, the biggest gray area is in the initial study material. There is still confounding regarding the experiences participants thought about. If the study picked consistent stimuli, there could possibly be a better control of the outcome.

On a scale of 0 - 1, this project has a replication of 0.25. A positive aspect of all the studies is that participants in the low-control condition did, on average have a higher pain score, even if not statistically significant. This work is likely in the Very Close to Exact Replication section, even though the initial survey material is not publicly available.
